wharmon@joseph.WPI.EDU (Warren Harmon) writes:

>In article <1993May4.154757.6662> lewis@aera8700.mitre.org
>(Keith Lewis) writes:

>[stuff about encrypting with a stronger (ie trusted) algorithm]
>[upstream of clipper deleted]

>>The encrypted message would have the clipper signature, but would not be
>>readable to "escrow agents" who couldn't break your backup encryption
>>scheme.

>This assumes that clipper's "signature" will be the same no matter
>what data is encrypted using it.  It might instead be possible that
>any voice waveform encrypted with clipper will be recognizeable as
>such, and will look different from other binary data (eg, voice
>encrypted with RSA) encrypted with clipper.

>And I'm sure that monitoring your phone line looking for anything that
>isn't (voice + clipper) will be ruled not to be search and seizure
>(and thus not require a warrant), just as getting a list of who you
>have been calling is not considered search and seizure.

I think there might be a difference. The list that you have been]
calling doesn't look at content at all. Indeed the line itself is
not monitored. In the case of monitoring for Clipper, the line itself
would have to be monitored, and monitored for exactly that which
would presumably be illegal. 

>Note: The above is entirely conjecture on my part.

